        <section id="Lok Biradari Prakalp (Hemalkasa)" class="section">
            <h2>Lok Biradari Prakalp (Hemalkasa)</h2>







<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," >

            <p>
         
Lok Biradari Prakalp (LBP) is a social project in Hemalkasa, a remote village in the Gadchiroli district of Maharashtra, India. It was started in 1973 by Dr. Prakash Amte, inspired by his father, the social activist Baba Amte. The project focuses on the integrated development of the Madia Gond tribal community in the region. 
In the initial years, the region was characterized by the absence of basic infrastructure like roads, electricity, and communication facilities, making it a challenging environment to work in. Despite these challenges, Dr. Prakash Amte and his wife Dr. Mandakini Amte dedicated their lives to serve the Madia Gond people. 
The LBP runs four main programs: a hospital, a school, an animal orphanage, and vocational training in areas like dairy, poultry, and bamboo craft. 
The hospital provides free medical care to the tribal population in the region, serving over 45,000 patients annually. The school provides education from primary to higher secondary levels and offers boarding and lodging facilities. In addition, it provides vocational training in skills like farming, seed production, and bamboo craft. The animal orphanage, known as Amte's Animal Ark, provides shelter to orphaned wild animals. The vocational training initiatives empower the tribal community by improving their skills and creating alternative livelihood options. 


            </p>

</section>






        <section id="Chaprala Wildlife Sanctuary" class="section">
            <h2>Chaprala Wildlife Sanctuary </h2>








<img src="  data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >
           <p>




Chaprala Wildlife Sanctuary, nestled in the Gadchiroli district of Maharashtra, India, is a haven of biodiversity, established in 1986 and spanning approximately 134.78 square kilometers. This sanctuary is renowned for its Southern Tropical Dry Deciduous Forests and grasslands, providing a diverse habitat for a rich variety of flora and fauna. The western border of the sanctuary is defined by the Pranhita River, a vital water source that significantly contributes to the area's ecological richness. The sanctuary's diverse flora includes dominant tree species such as teak, Arjun, Salai, and Mahua, alongside shrubs and grasses that support herbivorous populations. Chaprala is particularly known for its diverse fauna, boasting roughly 131 species of wild animals including predators like the Bengal tiger, leopard, sloth bear, and wild dog, as well as herbivores such as sambar deer, spotted deer, barking deer, and blue bull (nilgai). Birdwatchers can delight in observing around 131 avian species, including peacocks and jungle fowl, with migratory birds adding seasonal vibrancy. The sanctuary is also home to reptiles such as the endangered Indian python and common Indian monitor. Adding to the sanctuary's unique character, it is also home to the indigenous Gond tribal community, whose traditional lifestyle reflects a close connection with the surrounding environment. The most favorable period for visiting the Chaprala Wildlife Sanctuary is between February and May, as the weather is pleasant and wildlife sightings are more common as animals congregate around water sources. The sanctuary can be accessed by air, rail, and road, with the nearest airport being Dr. Babasaheb Ambedkar International Airport in Nagpur (approximately 243 km away), and Ballarpur Railway Station (approximately 70 km away) serving as the closest railhead. Visitors can find accommodation at the forest guesthouse in Chaprala or consider staying in nearby Chandrapur where hotels and lodges are available. Beyond the sanctuary itself, visitors can explore attractions such as Prashant Dham, Chaprala Temple, and the ancient Markanda Temple, which offer insights into the region's historical and cultural significance. To ensure a responsible and rewarding experience, visitors are encouraged to opt for guided tours, adhere to safety guidelines regarding wildlife, maintain a safe distance, avoid loud noises, and contribute to preserving the sanctuary's pristine environment by avoiding littering and carrying reusable water bottles. 





        </p>
        </section>






        <section id="Wadadham Fossil Park" class="section">
            <h2>Wadadham Fossil Park</h2>








<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >
            <p> 

                

Wadadham Fossil Park, situated in the Sironcha taluka of Gadchiroli District, Maharashtra, stands as a prominent paleontological site known for its significant dinosaur fossil discoveries. This park is particularly remarkable as it's the only dinosaur site in the Indian subcontinent showcasing fossils of both flora and fauna from the same geological period. Within its half-square-kilometer expanse, the park houses fossilized remains of huge sauropod dinosaurs like the Barapasaurus, a large, long-necked herbivore, alongside fish and tree fossils dating back approximately 150-160 million years to the Jurassic period, according to Quora}. Fossils found within the park include a well-preserved claw, a series of vertebrae, and broken limb bones like the femur, humerus, tibia, and radiale, with some parts even suggesting the presence of juvenile dinosaurs. The park also boasts fossils of trees such as Glossopteris and Dadoxylon conifers, indicating a forested landscape during the Jurassic period when these giant sauropods roamed. Beyond dinosaur and tree fossils, per Wikipedia, the area has also yielded Paleolithic stone tools, hinting at the presence of early humans around 2.5 million years ago. The discovery of a nearly complete Barapasaurus skeleton in 1959 near the Godavari basin further cemented Wadadham's importance, with the fossilized skeleton currently housed in a Kolkata museum. The Maharashtra Forest Department, in collaboration with the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI) and other bodies, has been developing the Wadadham Fossil Park, with plans for a fossil park spread across 2 hectares featuring replicas, bones, and plant fossils, as well as over 100 exhibits. The park is located near the village of Wadadham in Sironcha taluka, 189 kilometers south of the Gadchiroli district headquarters and 19 kilometers from Sironcha, according to National Portal of India. The nearest airport is Nagpur (380 km), and the closest railway station is Chandrapur. This site is expected to boost tourism and generate employment in the region once the development is complete. 


</p>

        </section>







        <section id="Markandadeo Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Markandadeo Temple</h2>









<img src=" data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >

<p>






    he Markandeshwar Temple, nestled on the banks of the Wainganga River in Maharashtra's Gadchiroli district, is an ancient temple complex dedicated to Lord Shiva, revered for its intricate carvings and historical significance. Often called the "Khajuraho of Vidarbha" due to the sculptural and architectural resemblance to the Khajuraho Temples in Madhya Pradesh, the complex is believed to have been constructed between the 8th and 12th centuries CE, primarily in the Hemadpanthi architectural style. Oral narratives and historical traditions link the temple's origins to the devout sage Markandeya who performed penance on this very site and was granted immortality by Lord Shiva, making it a sacred place for those seeking blessings and longevity. 
The temple complex originally featured twenty-four temples but only six are currently accessible to the public, however, these remaining structures still showcase the architectural marvels of the time. The temples are characterized by detailed carvings depicting scenes from the Ramayana, Mahabharata, other mythological tales, and representations of celestial beings, animals, and everyday life. The main shrine features a Linga, believed by local traditions to be the one worshipped by Markandeya himself. The temple's strategic riverside location likely played a significant role in its development during the early medieval period, when rivers served as vital routes for trade and transportation. 

</p>
        </section>


        <section id="Surjagarh Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Surjagarh Fort</h2>







<img src="   data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >

            <p> 


               Surajgarh Fort, also known as the "Castle of the Sun", is a captivating heritage property located in the town of Surajgarh, Rajasthan. Constructed in 1778 by Thakur Suraj Mal (1768-1787) of the BissaU (Thikana) Shekhawat (Sadhani clan), this historic fort initially served to provide employment to local villagers and to defend against bandits and invading armies. The palace's name, Surajgarh, literally means "The Castle of The Sun", a testament to its grandeur and historical significance. 
The fort's history is deeply intertwined with the bravery of its founder, Thakur Suraj Mal, whose prosperous reign ended tragically in 1787 during the Battle of Tunga, where he fought against the Marathas led by Mahadji Scindhia. 
Today, Surajgarh Fort is being meticulously restored to offer guests a unique experience of living like a Maharaja. It is particularly renowned for its breathtaking frescoes, which were created using traditional materials like crushed cowrie shells, lime, and locally sourced vegetable dyes. The fort's transformation into a heritage hotel allows visitors to immerse themselves in Rajasthan's rich history and architectural beauty. 

</p>
        </section>

        <section id="Glory of Allapalli (Van Vaibhav)" class="section">
            <h2>Glory of Allapalli (Van Vaibhav)</h2>


            
           




<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >
            <p>  
      

                The "Glory of Allapalli", also known as Van Vaibhav, is a significant biodiversity heritage site in Maharashtra, India. This 6-hectare patch of ancient forest is located 16 km (9.9 miles) east of Allapalli village in the Gadchiroli district, on the road towards Bhamragad. Its importance was recognized as early as 1867 by the British, leading to its conservation efforts in 1953 and eventual declaration as Maharashtra's first Biodiversity Heritage Site in 2014. The site serves as a permanent preservation plot for studying the Allapalli forest in its natural state. It boasts a rich diversity of over 130 floral species, including tree species such as teak, tendu, dhawala, kusum, and yen, and medicinal plants like gunj, tarota, and gulwel. The area showcases a three-stage flora with abundant plant and animal species and is managed to maintain a natural ecosystem, fostering the presence of various insects, spiders, algae, and fungi. Notable features include some of the state's largest teak trees, with the tallest recorded at 39.70 meters and the largest at 5.27 meters girth at breast height. The ecosystem extends to the Medpalli Lake, drawing both tourists and researchers. Best visited between October and February, the site also benefits from fire protection efforts, resulting in a thick layer of humus on the forest floor. 


</p>

        </section>

        <section id="Somnur Sangam" class="section">
            <h2>Somnur Sangam</h2>


            
           



<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >

<p>


Somnur Sangam, located in Gadchiroli, Maharashtra, India, is a tourist attraction known for its confluence of rivers and scenic beauty. It's specifically recognized for the convergence of the Godavari and Indravati rivers. Some also refer to it as the confluence point of the Pamulgautam, Indravati & Parlkota rivers. This location is considered a beautiful natural spot, with reports mentioning the presence of holy rivers, a great nature view, and interesting stones. It's described as being amidst mountains. The area offers free admission and doesn't require advance booking. The sunset views at the confluence are said to be a treat for tourists, and the area is home to dense forests and tribal cultures. Nearby attractions include the Wadadham Fossil Park, Vairagad Fort, and Gurvala Nature Safari. The area is well-connected by road, with bridges recently completed on the Pranhita and Godavari Rivers connecting Sironcha to neighboring districts and states. The region has even revealed discoveries of dinosaur fossils. 



</p>
   
        </section>

        <section id="Vairagad Fort & Bhandareshwar" class="section">
            <h2>Vairagad Fort & Bhandareshwar</h2>



            


           

<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >

            <p>

Vairagad Fort, also known as Vairatgad, is a historic fort near Wai Vyajwadi in the Satara district of Maharashtra, India. It stands strategically on a hilltop, providing panoramic views of the surrounding landscape. 
The fort's history dates back to the 11th century when it was built by King Bhoj of the Shilahar Dynasty. It served as a military station during King Shivaji's reign and was captured by the British in 1818. According to GKToday, the Lunar Dynasty's King Vairacan established the fort, which later became a Gond stronghold, and Wikimedia Commons mentions the Mana Nagavanshi dynasty also ruled the region before the Gonds. 
The fort spans a 10-acre area north of the village. It features three gates, a river moat 15 to 20 feet deep, and several wells, including a stepwell with two arches. Efforts are underway for the reconstruction of the main entrance. Outside the fort, visitors can find the tomb of the Gond Prince Durga Sah and the grave of an unknown English girl, believed to be the daughter of a British commandant from the early 19th century. 
                
            </p>
</section>

        <section id="Semana Temple & Gadchiroli Lake" class="section">
            <h2>Semana Temple & Gadchiroli Lake</h2>







<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >
            <p>
         
Gadchiroli, a district in eastern Maharashtra known for its dense forests and rich tribal culture, is home to a few notable attractions, including  (which seems to be referred to as Semana Temple) located approximately 4 km from the town center and the Gadchiroli Lake situated in the heart of the city. 
The Gadchiroli Lake, while offering a natural setting, faces challenges due to increased human activity such as urbanization and washing with detergents, leading to elevated levels of carbonates and nutrients that indicate the water quality has deteriorated and the lake is becoming eutrophic. Despite this, the lake and its periphery support a variety of bird species, with some studies recording up to 40 species belonging to 27 families, particularly in the wetlands surrounding the lake. The ResearchGate analysis of Avifauna diversity suggests that the Gadchiroli lake and other similar lakes in the district retain high biological diversity and serve as a pathway for birds, indicating the importance of conserving the lake and its surroundings for both terrestrial and water-dependent birds. 


</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Kamalapuri Elephant Camp" class="section">
            <h2>Kamalapuri Elephant Camp</h2>








            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Description of image" >

 <p>  
    


    amalapur Elephant Camp, located in the village of Kamalapur, Aheri Taluka, Gadchiroli District, Maharashtra, is the only government elephant camp in the state. It's situated amidst a scenic landscape, with elephants inhabiting an area near a lake and mountains, according to Mindtrip. The camp is a significant tourist attraction in Gadchiroli, which is typically known as a Naxalite affected region. 
Visitor experience
The camp is a popular destination, attracting over 50 tourists daily and more than 150 on weekends. Visitors can interact with the elephants, with the opportunity to observe them up close, feed them under staff guidance, and take photos. Early mornings are recommended for observing the elephants bathing and feeding. While the elephants are generally well-behaved, visitors are cautioned against disturbing them. 
Elephant care and welfare
The camp houses several elephants, including Basanti (95 years), Rupa (80), Mangala (34), Ajit (28), Rani (14), Priyanka (12), Ganesh (11), and Laxmi (9 months), who share an emotional bond with the local community. The camp has faced criticism regarding its elephant management practices, particularly concerning the elephants being chained. However, some sources clarify that chaining occurs only at night to protect them from wild elephants or during aggressive mating periods. Additionally, there's a need for more trained staff and resources to ensure optimal elephant welfare, as highlighted by concerns raised following the death of an elephant named Aditya. 


</p>
